{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_braniff_ver01/data/sn83045433/00294558135/1914032401/0672.xml":{"full_text":"WW V \"OTS?\nE?3!\nRS'.'1\nvvcvire?\nV.ir,.\nPf.u v1\n\nv t? v-.-s v y&p&\nri-t- rvc-1 ,1\nFSjrv, jh -r\n.-t\nit\nf\n-i\nTHE WASHINGTON HERALD. TUESDAY, MARCH 24, 1914.-\nPemH\nTHE WASHINGTON HERALD\nrabtbbtd Km? Uoralz is tie Tear b\n1EE WASHINGTON HERALD COMPANY\nftkpbeu iUSa SXO. (Print Brtsch ExchisfO\nPUBLICATION OITICE.\n1322 NEW YORE fi.mX N. W.\nEntered tt tbt poatorBc. t Wiahlnftna. 0,0.1\ntttoDj-din snttl matter.\nn te-S.t J. ttwaBBBDaea.\nSFXCIAL AGEiCI. Braniwfck BaOfflat\nCWo BersarUtltt. 3. KS1X0B. M\nHartford BafliHrr,\nAtUnne CUT BeprtsttUOTt. C. K. ABBOT.\nEsrtlctt BottSJct.\nNo attention -til bo paid to wg\nmous contributions, and no com??:\nUona to the editor will i5?tedTn,S\ncept over the nam of thy writer. xn'\nmist not contain over So word.\nManuscript offered for jraoUcatlon i will\nDeretirrned If unaTallable. but ump\nsfcottia bi sent with the manuacrlpt for\nthat purpose.\nBCBSCHiWlOJJ BATES BT CARBJKB\nUaTrj tad Boncay -?\"JLrith\nDally, without Boadiy. i0\" ,BUl\nscBSCBirnoN bates bt iiao.\nDior tad Eradty '\"g-FLfar\nDally tad Bandar -TJJS\nDally. aoat Sraeuy. \"SmUfTS\nDaBy. wtthort Baadw. J\nBmday. without Duy .pr\nTUESDAY. MARCH 1311\nWhat has become of the old-time free\ndom that used to shriek?\nPresident Wilson may wear a velvet\nslipper, but he doesn't tango in it.\n\"Would jou for twenty millions?\"\nasks a theatrical ad. We certainly would.\nSome of the I. W. W. crowd in New\nYork are kept busy trjing to keep out\nof work.\nYou should try to keep up the bluff\non All Fools' Day just as ou do on all\nother dajs.\nSome people's idea of personal lib\nerty is to keep other people from doing\nwhat they want to do.\nSome men never realize that they\ncannot make a good showing by sim\nply puffing and blowing.\nIf Father Noah were lining today he\nwould probably ask Congress for an\nappropriation for a levee.\nPittsburgh should not worry about the\nmoney that Billy Sunday took out of\nthe town. He will put it to good use.\nVilla is holding a Mexican for $250,000\nransom. Would ou give that much\nmoney for any Mexican you eer saw?\nThat Pennsjlvania machine jou may\nbreak it, you may shatter it if jou will,\nbut the odor of Penrose will cling to\nit stilL\nIt is being whispered around that the\nfriends of former Congressman Thistle\nwood thinks he would make good Sen\natonal timber.\nHappy childhood days, down on the\nfarm! About this time of jear mother\nused to begin dosing us with great dabs\nof sulphur and molasses.\nThose who wondered why Joe Folk\nshould accept a $5,000 government job\nnow understand it. It was merely a\nstepping stone to a $10,000 one.\nRcprescntativ e Decker sajs the na\ntion owes a great debt to the lawyers.\nWell, if it docs the lawjcrs will collect\nit Mr. Decker need not worry-\nPeople of Sweden are demanding\nhigher taxes so they may strengthen\ntheir army and navy. Respectfully re\nferred to the Committee on Immigra\ntion. A Senator's son, three Capitol police\nmen in uniform, one white and several\ncolored messengers in a friendly poker\ngame in a Senate committee room.\nSure: Isn't this a Democratic adminis\ntration2 Would you rather be the man who\nspent five jears coloring a meerschaum\npipe and then lost it, or the chap who\nsmoked one brand of cigarettes until he\ngot enough coupons to win a grand\npiano and then had them stolen?\nA man has been acrrsed of setting\nfire to a building and then turning in a\nfalse alarm. The only reason that he\ncannot set up the pica that the first\ncharge disproves the second is that the\nalarm was turned in far from the scene\nof 'he incendiary blaze.\nCommittees from the chambers of\ncommerce of Washington and Baltimore\nare to meet today to take steps to have\nthe proposed Lincoln highway pass\nthrough both Baltimore and Washing'\nton. What sort of a Lincoln highway\nwould it be if it did not include the\nCapital?\n\"Carl Hopf, the druggist of this city\nwho has been named the 'Bluebeard of\nGermany,\" was beheaded today for mur\ndering his father, his first wife and his\ntwo children\" A scrap from some his\ntory of the Middle Ages? Oh, no, just\na news dispatch, dated Frankfort-on-the-Main,\nGermany, March 23, 1914.\nSenator John Sharp Williams, of Mis\nsissippi, served timely warning jesterday\nregarding the large sums being spent on\ninvestigations and inquiries by rarious\nSenate committees. The old \"economy\"\ncry has been raised on several occasions\nrecently, and jet it develops that ex\npenditures from the contingent fund of\nthe Senate have increased over $50,000\nin the last) car.\nIke Prptekst ud Trait LepeUiw.\nOur President is giving further itmi\nonstration of his caliber and high intent\nin his attitude toward the trust legisla\ntion which he is striving to bring to the\nstandards of real statecraft.\nHis original notice that the Five\nBrothers are not administration meas\nures, in the sense that the tariff and\ncurrency acts w ere, was an adroit and\ntimely move worthy of more than pass\ning mention and attention.' It made\ngenuine the invitation for comment and\naid from, the business men of the coun\ntry because it was notice to them that\ntheir appearance in Washington did not\nconstitute political opposition to the\nPresident and his administration. It\nbrought them to Washington by the\nscore, in the exercise of their better\nrights and duties as citizens, and gave\nthe administration a great volume of\nvaluable information. This information\nwas the more accurate and useful and\neffective because it was delivered in an\natmosphere free of the prejudicial in\nflunces that would have been at play in\nother circumstances. It was bidden to a\nfield meant to be free and fair.\nThis information, with the manifestly\nclose study that the President and his\nadvisers in and out of Congress are giv\ning to the several vitally important ques\ntions that arc involved, reflects itself in\nthe attitude and course of the President\nand his lieutenants. The real danger in\nthe situation is already passed. It was\nthat Congress would attempt too much\nand do little of it well. Study, inquiry\nand observation, made on the eve of the\nassumption of responsibility for legisla\ntion freighted with large consequence to\nthe people at large, and to the party,\nhave revealed to the strong man at the\nhelm and to the leaders in Congress that\nthere lies ahead of them a task that\ncalls for the most serious analytic and\nconstructive effort they can put forth.\nMuch that the President and the de\npendable leaders of the party are doing\nindicates that they are in full realization\nof the delicacy and importance of their\nlegislative problem and the folly of un\nwise and unfair legislation.\nThe truth of this statement is exem\nplified by the recently announced de\ncision of the President to abandon the\nattempt to define by statute the so-called\ndoubtful features of the Sherman act\nStudy, counsel and conference convinced\nthe President that he and his party stood\nin danger of trading certainty for un\ncertainty and its resulting confusion and\ndestruction, and with sense and courage\nthat do him honor he decided to go no\nfarther on that line. He has not made\nclear his entire position on the question\nbut he appears to be resolved to rely\nupon the rule of reason dictum, with\nintent\" as the factor to be decided by\nthe courts, and to endeavor to make the\ngreat law more effective by fixing and\npenalizing personal responsibility for the\nacts shown in court to be in contraven\ntion of the law. In this wise deter\nmination he will be applauded and sup\nported by all who strive for real solu\ntion of the ills that are to be remedied.\nThe President has shown that he is\ngoing into the other leatures of the\npending legislation with the same\nthoughtful care, and his sane stand\nought to insure beneficial legislation.\nThere are several evils of business\nthat the people and their government\nare resolved to ban by laws that will\npunish heavily those who willfully traf\nfic in those evils But in striving to\nreach the guilty it is essential to pro\ntect the innocent from unjust and un\nnecessary punishment, and it is equally\nessential that the business of the coun\ntry should not be fettered.\nHere in the rough is the problem that\nour President and his party must en\ngage, and upon their wisdom and jus\ntice in dealing with it will depend the\njudgment of them that the country will\nrecord at the elections in 1914 and 1916.\nThat the President realizes all this is\nmade clear by the sensible course he is\nfollowing.\nNew Hope in Mexico.\nA correspondent of the New York\nSun, referring to President Wilson's\nMexican policy, compares him to the\nIrish soldier who, when told by the\ndrill sergeant that he was out of step,\nretorted that the trouble was not with\nhim, but that all the rest of the regi\nment were out ot step. This writer\nmakes the point that while all the rest\nof the world believes recognition of\nHuerta the proper and necessary course.\nPresident Wilson persists in his belief\nthat he is right in refusing.\nThere is an accumulation of evidence\nin favor of the assumption that if this\ngovernment had recognized Huerta the\nMexican problem would now be a thine\nof the past. If the President could but\nhave seen his way to an admission\nmonths ago that by reason of misin\nformation he was mistaken in his orig-\ninal position and had extended recog\nnition t'o the only visible 'authority or\nform of government in Mexico, hun\ndreds of lives would have been saved\nand the world would have been spared\nthe bloody tragedy now being enacted\nabout Torreon.\nIfit should transpire that events now\nshaping in Mexico will enable the Presi\ndent to recognize some authority which\nthis government may hold to account\nfor murder and outrage the entire coun\ntry will rejoice;\n\"Spok for Yonwlf, John.\"\nWe had occasion several days ago to\nquote President Rea, of the Pennsyl-J\nvania Railroad, in this column and we\nagain quote him and once more it is\nto point a moral and adorn a tale. Speak\ning to the stockholders of the railroad\nat their annual meeting be denounced\nas false the assertion that the manage\nment under his direction had been tech\nnically manipulating the accounts for\nthe purpose of showing that the cost\nof operation had increased to an ex\ntent greater than it actually had, -and\nmade this declaration of intent:\nYour management is determined\nthat within the limits of reason it\nwill hereafter allow no statement to\ngo unchallenged that reflects on the\nmanagement or the integrity of its\nofficers.\nIn speaking thus Mr. Rea was really\ngiving voice to a broader policy than\nhis words would indicate; a policy that\nfor some time past has been forming in\nthe minds and shaping in the acts of\nprogressive railway men all over the\ncountry. It is a policy that does not\nconfine itself and concern itself merely\nwith the denunciation and refutal of\nspecific misstatements but one that\ntouches the whole range of railway re\nlationship to the public\nFor a variety of reasons indifferent.\nbad and good, it was long the practice\nof most railroad men to ignore or dis\nregard most of tile criticism, good, bad\nand indifferent, directed at them and\ntheir roads. It was a most unwise prac\ntice and why it obtained for so many\nyears is a good deal of a mvstery. But\nit did persist over many decades and if\nrailway men gave thought to it and its\nunwisdom they said little or nothing\nabout it and they certainly did little or\nnothing about it. And they did not act\nuntil that stern parent. Necessity, stirred\nthem to action.\nOf course, it ought to be borne in\nmind that during all this time the rail\nroad men had a few other things to\nthink about. Thej were working to the\nlimit of the physical side of the coun\ntry's transportation problem and it was\na struggle to meet its daily increasing\nneeds. And their accomplishment stands\nas a monument to American intelligence\nand energy.\nMeantime, during all the j ears that the\nrailway men had been silent or indif\nferently talkative the fellows on the\nother side had not been idle for a mo\nment. In the press and on the platform,\nin and out of eason they kept ham\nmering away. Some of their agitation\nand attack was fair and justifiable, some\nof it was unfair and unjustifiable. But\nthey had the stage all to themselves\nand the result was inevitable. A tre\nmendous volume of adverse sentiment,\nquite lopsided, was piled up and that\nsentiment, with the power of a million\nlocomotives is making itself felt all over\nthe country. Its power is everywhere\nfelt and nowhere to greater extent than\nin instrumentalities of the State created\nby popular vote instrumentalities ju\ndicial in theory, prejudicial in fact.\nThe trend of several events culminate\nin a desperate crisis to the transporta\ntion sjstem of the country and when the\nrailway men turn to the people for as\nsistance and relief what do they find?\nAn almost solid wall of adverse senti\nment, shortsighted in its vision, undis\ncerning in its knowledge and quite\nstolid. For the lack of understanding\nmost of the railway men are themselves\nto blame. THEY HAVE NEVER\nTOLD THEIR STORY TO THE\nPEOPLE. It is their fault that only\none side of the shield has been seen.\nThe way to the public ear and mind\nhas alwajs been clear and most of the\nrailway men who have found and\ntraveled it have had a very agreeable\nexperience. They have found the peo\nple ready to listen and learn, quick in\nunderstanding and willing to help when\nthe appeal has been justly grounded.\nThis is the policy to which Mr. Rea\ngives voice and it is a policy that is\nspreading among the brethren of the rail\nall over the countrj-. In his experience\nwith the New Haven Howard Elliott\nhas found his chief support in the in\nformed public sentiment of New Eng\nland to which he has spoken with free\ndom and candor. Out on the Pacific\nCoast when recently the government\nproposed the demerging of two railway\nlines it was the people who made the\nstrongest pica in behalf of the railroad\nexecutives. Other railway lines have\ntold their story to the people of their\nterritory and frankness has been met by\nfairness.\nAnd o it must be all over the coun\ntry. There is much more to the trans\nportation problem than simply taking it\nout of the hides of certain properties\nand their shareholders and solution will\ncome in an established ratio of time to\npublic understanding.\nA good many jears ago a prim Puri\ntan maiden said: \"Spealc for yourself\nJohn,\" and the homely injunction is one\nthat most Americans like to see put in\npractice in all the common relations of\nmen.\nAN OPEN LETTER TO THE L C. C.\nImpelled, he explains, by \"a knowl\nedge of current conditions and of pos\nsible dangers,\" Mr. B. C Forbes, bust\nness editor of the New York Ameri\ncan, has written an open letter to the\nmembers of the Interstate Commerce\nCommission, in which he forcefully de\nscribes the national railway crisis and\nmakes strong appeal for early and in\ntelligent action by the governing body.\nHere is the letter:\nGentlemen of the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission:\nAre jou aware that, partly owing\nto your course of action, the country\nIs In peril. of suffering; an upheaval\ndisastrous to labor, to the railroads,\nto Investors, to Industry, to the public\nat large and to the administration?\nDo you realize that In Jour hands\nhave been placed responsibilities com\nparable only with those devolving\nupon tho Supreme Court of the United\nStates?\nYou have been given control of the\ngreatest Industry in the country, its\nsystem of transportation, on whose\nwelfare depends, directly or Indirectly,\nthe welfare of every man, woman and\nchild in the Union.\nYou aro responsible to Congress\nalone.\nYou are more than a quasi-Judicial\nbody; there have been reposed In ou\nadministrative functions of the grav\nest Importance.\nNow, rightly or wronglj, jour ac\ntions have created the very general\nbelief that. Instead of holding the\nscales of Justice even between the\nrailroads and shippers, you have be\ncome an antl-rallroad body.\nIn ruling perhaps wlsclj against\nthe Increase in freight rates applied\nfor In 1910 jou gave reasons which\nwere supported by arguments and sta\ntistics embodjing serious misrepre\nsentation of facts. Your misuse of\nfigures on that occasion raised doubts\nin well-Informed minds of jour desire\n-or jour abllltj'-to be strictly im\npartial In dealing with large railroad\nand financial problems.\nSince then the position of our rail\nroads has grown distinctly worse,\nThe confidence of Investors, both In\nEurope and at home, has been so\nshaken that many roads are today In\na parlous financial atate.\nDuring the jears 1914. 1915 and 191\nmaturing railroad obligations alone\nwill call for upward of Sl.OUO.000.000\nthis without providing one dollar of\nadditional capital for any purpose\nwhatsoever.\nHow debts falling due are to be\nmet and 'hew capital necessary to\nmaintain solvency Is to be raised are\nproblems now exercising grave concern\nIn the financial and railroad world.\nWhether these problems can be\nhandled without plunging the country\nInto general disaster depends In large\nmeasure upon the course you choose to\nfollow Th ajcf. if financial Europe\nand of thinking American citizens are\nupon vou at this moment, anxiously\nawaiting announcement of jour pollcj'.\nThe State of mind existing today In\nthe most responsible circles Is not\nconducive to that speedj- return of\nprosperity which the deplorable prev\nalence of unempiojment and discon\ntent renders so cxtremelj desirable.\nWithout overstating the facts. It can\nbe said that those who are charged\nwith the task of directing and man\naging the country s railroads are In\ndanger. If further drnled the co\noperation of the government and\njour liodj, of abandoning as hopeless\nall efforts to overcome multipoint\ndifficulties\nI beg jou to ponder these words ut\ntered this week bj bamuel Ren, presi\ndent of the Pennsjlvania Railroad.\nThis statement is not made to pre\ndict calamity, but It is made to pre\nvent calamltj\nThere is more need than jou, per\nhaps realize, for efforts \"to prevent\ncalamity\nWhnt are jou gentlemen of the In\nterstate Commerce Commission, jou\nguardians of the nation's railroads,\ndoing to prevent calamltj'\nOne of j our number has Just cauol\nto be published In ensatIonaI manner,\ncharges of \"serious tmgularltleV\nagainst the Chicago. Milwaukee S. ht\nI'aul Rallwaj, which \"irregularities\"\n-confined whollj to bookkceplng\nwere committed several jears ago\nand pointed out at tl.it time by tho\nfinancial precs.\nHas It taken jou three jears to dis\ncover what the financial press dis\ncovered Immedlatelj the company Is\nsued its annual report\nIf not. whj is tne ubjrct treated\nby jou so sen'atiunallj at this un\nfortunate Juncture, when the solvency\nof numbers of railroads and the posi\ntion of the railroads as n whole are\noccasioning so much concern and mili\ntating \"o strongly against a revival In\nbusiness which, if much longer de\nlayed, cannot but lead to unhappy con\nsequences to gov eminent and gov\nerned alike\nNot content to aggravate the un\nrest by harking baik at this Juncture\nto a three-j ear-old Incident admitted\nly indefensible, jou add the alarming\nstatement that \"In MANY Instances\"\nsimilar irregularities have been per\npetrated. Why this vague, panic-breeding al\nlegation\nAre jou concealing wrongdoing by\nMANY other roads?\nIs it jour intention to explode these\nbombs periodically, whenever jour\nfancj. or what jou may regard as\nexpedlencj-. dictates\nWhy single out one railroad for ex\nposure and shield MANY OTHERS\nyou know tu be equally guilty?\nCan you not see how disquieting Is\nthe effect of jour verj serious allega\ntion How arc Investors to know that the\nroad whose securities they hold Is not\none of the MANY who have juggled\ntheir accounts to flimflam the public?\nThe St. Paul's shares shrank Ji.uoo.OM\nIn market value on j'our unexpected\nand alarmist announcement.\nAre other stocks to be forced down\nequal amounts from time to time,\nwhenever jou see lit to expose the\nMANY guilty companies?\nGentlemen, I ask jou to consider\nwhether the time for purposeless re\ncrimination has not pased.\nI ask jou to consider whether the\ntime hasanot come to cease DE\nSTRUCTIVE action and to concen\ntrate upon a CONSTRUCTIVE pollcj'.\nYou have before jou, and have had\nbefore jou for many months, an ap\nplication bj- Eastern railroads for per\nmission to increase their freight rates\n5 per cent.\nTho railroads have co-operated with\njou in supplying all needful facts to\nJudge their case.\nCan jou not expedite jour delibera\ntions? An attempt has been made of late\nto cite other avenues of relief and the\nimpression has been spread that the\nrailroads have been \"discovered\" in\ndulging in varloufe practices calculated\nto unreasonably deplete their Income.\nYou gentlemen know that these\npractices, one and all. have been done\nIn acordance with established uage\nand under arrangements never onco\nprohibited by you\nYet I am not aware that jou have\nput the public right in their concep\ntion of the position, although a state\nment from jou would have clarified\nthe atmosphere and tended In some\ndegree to allay the antl-rallroad sen\ntiment now so prevalent and so In\njurious to the whole nation.\nAbolition of these various entrenched\npractices cannot be ordered or effected\nHISTORY BUILDERS.\nA Curious Fact Concerning American\nex-Presidents.\n(Written Expressly for The Herald.')\nBy II n. E. J. CDWiitDS.\nA year or two after Abrnm S. Hewitt\nfinished his term as mayor of New York\nCity I spent an hour with him at a time\nwhen he was disposed to be reminiscent\nand reflect! e. I asked him If he renum\nbered aconversatlon he liad In ISS3 as\nwe rode together from his Washington\nhome, near Jackson Square, to the Capi\ntol. Mr. Hewitt was at that time a njem\nber of Congress. He asked me to what\nI referred and I said to him that I had\ncalled his attention to a paragraph which\nhad appeared In a newspaper In which\nMr. Hewitt was recommended as a Dem\nocratic candidate for the Presidential\nnomination of 1SS4.\n\"Do you .remember what you said to\nme when I called your attention to this\nparagraph?\" I asked him.\nHe said that ha had not the slightest\nrecollection, then told him that he said:\n\"I am the last man who ought to enter\ntho White House as President. The re\nsponsibilities and annoyances and con\nfusion would kill me within three months.\nThey killed President William Henry\nHarrison in one.\"\nMr. Hewitt smiled grimly and then\nsaid:\n\"No doubt I thought so then. But\nI now know that any man .of consclenv\ntlous Durbose who is able to serve asl\nmajor of New York for two years with\nout breaking down completely would be\nablo to live through a Presidential term.\n\"I am astonished sometimes when I\nthink of the mental and physical strain I\nendured during my term is mayor of\nNew York. In my opinion. If a mayor\nIs absolutely conscientious and is anxious\nto be something more than a mere figure\nhead, the office Is the most trying one\nany American citizen can hold.\"\nHo was silent for a few moments and.\nI thought, was about to revert to some\nof the grievous annoyances and the dif\nficult encounters with the bosses jjrhlch\nwere a part of his experiences as a\nmajor. Instead of that he spoke of an\nentirely different matter, saying: \"I won\nder If It has ever occurred to any one\nbut mjsclf what a brief term of life the\ngreat majority of our Presidents, at least\nsince lttO. had after they retired from\ntho White House. This thought occurred\nto me one day and so forcibly that 1 de\ntermined to look Into the histories of ex\nPresldents. I found to my astonishment\nthat while with the exception of Monroe,\nall of the Presidents between Jefferson\nand Van Buren lived several years after\ntheir retirement from the Presidency, a\nstrange mortality appeared to cut short\nthe lives of almost all of those who\nserved In that office after James K. Tolk\ndied\n\"Monroe lived only a few years after\nhe retired, and I have been told that one\nof the chief causes of his early death was\nthe sense of humiliation that he should\nhave been compelled to rely somewhat\nupon the benefaction of others for his\nsupport.\n\"Polk lived only a hort time after he\nretired from the Presidency. Millard\nFillmore survived longer than almost\nall the others I remember to have seen\nMartin Van Buren early In 116. He was\nih.n vigorous, although he had been\ntwenty -one years out of the Presidency.\n\"Andrew Johnson naa oniy a snori who\nto live after he retired from the Presl-\ndencj\". Gen Grant retired in is.i ana\ndied in li Arthur lived a little over\na j ear after he retired, in lsSi Presi\ndent Ilaje lived twelve jears.\n\"I find myself wondering wneiner tne\nvery great strain to which a President Is\nMinject. at least in these later days of\nour Intense acllvuj. aid noi tena 10 sap\ntheir strength. I don't know whether\nthl Is so or not. but 1 do know that the\nav erase vears remaining for an ex-rresi-\ndent of the United State\", at least since\nIK, have been not much over ten. Did\njou ever think how few the number of\nliving ex-Presidents has been That\nthought has very ofUn occurred to me.\"\nToniomiiT Dr. Kdnards nill tell\n\"What Might Have Happened to Col.\nVAatlerson.\"\n(CorjrUbt. 1J1I 1\nLINCOLN RELICS TO BE SOLD.\nEdwin Booth's first letter after he re\nceived the new that his brother had\nkilled Abraham Lincoln, full of agonized\nhorror at the deed. Is among the manu\nscripts to be dispersed at the sale of the\nfourth part of the MaJ William II. Lam\nbert collection of Lincolnlana. at the\nAnderson Art Galleries Madison avenue\nand Fortieth street, beginning April 1.\nThe letter, which was written to Col A.\nBadrau. sajs In part\nFor the flirt time since the damnable\nIntelligence stunned me that ray brother\nWilkes enacted this fearful, hellish deed\nam I able to wrl'e You must feel deeply\nthe agony I bear In being thus blasted in\nall mj hopes by a villain who seemed so\nlovable, and In whom all his family found\na source of Joj In his boyish and confid\ning nature Abraham Lincoln was my\nPresident, for In pure admiration of hl\nnoble career and Christian principles I\ndid what I never did before I voted, and\nfor him\nAnother relic of Interest Is an auto\ngraph page from the sum book of Lin\ncoln, dating from 1K1 On\" side of the\nleaf Is entitled Simple Interest Exam\nples\" and the other 'Simple Interest.\"\nNear the first heading Mr. Herndon,\nLincoln's law partner, has written \"Genu\nine. W. II Herndon The eleven exam\nples and two rules are set down In full\nby Lincoln. Mr. Herndon obtained sev\neral pages of the sum book from Lin\ncoln's stepmother and presented them to\nhis Intimate friends.\nAnother relic Is a cane, with buckhorn\nhandle and silver trimming\", used bj- Lin\ncoln and bearing this Inscription- \"Pre\nsented to Abraham Lincoln by his old\nfriend S. Strong. 1W Each knob on\nthe cane bears a small sliver plate con\ntaining one letter, and reading from top\nto bottom the letters form the name of\nAbraham Lincoln. The cane was pre-\nsented by Mrs. Lincoln to Mr. Frank B. 1\nCarpenter.\nAmong the documents is a copy of the\nEmancipation Proclamation.\" signed by\nLincoln and William H. Seward and at\ntested by John G Nlcolay, secretary to\nthe President. It Is one of fifty dupllcato\nauthorized copies of the proclamation.\nAnother document Is a duplicate of the\nthirteenth amendment to the Constitu\ntion, signed by the members of Congress\nwho voted for It. New York Herald.\nhastily. Exhaustive Investigation will\nbe necessary before overthrowing the\nstatus quo.\nHence no adequate relief can be ob\ntained at this time from such source\",\nalthough later on substantial read\njustments may be possible for the\nbenefit of the railroads.\nI would respectfullj ask jou to\nconsider the advisability of granting,\nat the earliest possible moment after\nthe conclusion of jour present hear\nings, tho Increased rates petitioned\nfor, supplemented. If need be. bj- a\nstatement that if developments amelio\nrate tho circumstances of the rail\nroads the higher rates maj- be can\ncelled at some future date\nA patient Is beyond medical aid once\nhe has died.\nThe Herald reproduces tins remark\nable letter from the American because\nof its strength and clarity and timeli\nness. Much of its ground has been cov\nered in this and other newspaper col\numns but possibly not so well as Mr.\nForbes has presented the case.\nStatesnei, Real and Near.\nBy FRED C KELLT.\nRepresentative and Senator-elect Rob\nert t Broussard. of Louisiana. Is kin to\nabout half the people In that State, or at\nleast, r.bout every other man he meets\nIn a campaign calls him \"Cousin Bob.\"\nHe speaks Louisiana French, which Is a\nlanguage entirely distinct from young-ladies'-nnlshlng-achoot\nFrench or Learn-to-speak-French-for-Sls\nFrench. Speaking\ntheir language as he does, \"Cousin Bob\"\nhas a strong hold on the people of his\nsection of the State,, and their main re\nligion is to vote for Bob Broussard with\nout question and without stint whenever\nhe runs for anything.\nWhen Broussard was running for the\nUnited States Senate, Representative\nJames B. -well was seeking election to\nthe lower house of Congress. Aswell was\ntalking to a man In the section where\nBroussard Is best known, and asked him\nfor his vote.\n\"No, I'm going to vote for Bob Bob\nBroussard,\" said the man.\n\"That's all right. You can vote for\nBob and for me, too.\" Aswell explained.\n\"We're not running for the same thing.\"\nThe man shook his head. \"No,\" says\nhe, \"I'll Just vote for Bob Then If you're\nentitled to have an office. Bob can ap\npoint you to It.\"\nRepresentative SlmeorrD Fess. of Onlo.\nneither smokes nor drinks. In conse\nquence of many years as a school and\ncollege teacher when he feared to set a\nbad example to the growing jouth of the\nland.\nWhen Representative Watson, of Vir\nginia the man who presided as judge\nover the famous Beatty murder case\nset out to studv law, his father gave\nhim one piece of advice. \"Keep out of\npontics.\" said his father. So Watson\nwent at once into politics. When he was\nt went j -one jears od he became a State\nSenator.\nAfter all. Luck, or Chance, cuts a\ngood deal of a figure Take the case of\nLouis FltzHenry, member of Congress\nfrom Illinois. FltzHenry started out un\nknown and practically penniless to build\nup a law practice It might have taken\nhim jean and years to pass the starva\ntion period except for Luck.\nWithin a day or so after FltzHenry\nwas admitted to the bar. a good friend\nof his emplojed by a railroad company\nhad a leg cut off Knowing that Fltz\nHenry was just starting out and needed\nhelp, the friend kindly emplojed htm as\nhis attorney to .ue the railroad for con\ntributory negligence\nThat case gave FltzHenry his chance.\nue won 11 ana tnen got many more\ndamage cases. Nobody thought of losing\nan arm or a leg without retaining Fitz\nHenry for attornej as soon afterward as\npossible In that waj he quicklj built\nup a reputation as a good damage law-\njer In his locality and made a good deal\nor money.\noui ne Knows nimself that It was\nlargely luck If he hadn't had the rood\nfortune to have a friend lose a leg. he\nmignt nave struggled along In obscurity\nfor jears and jears\nRepresentative Claude Weaver. a\nbrlght-ejed little Representative from\nUKianoma, rarely turns a book agent\nirom nis door empty-handed His of\nfice looks like a branch library and the\nbooks are learned books None of jour\nGeorge McCutcheon and Harold McGrath\nlor Weaver. Moreover, everj book on\nhis shelves has its pages cut Weaver\nhas books to read and not merely to take\ntne placo of wainscoting, or to Impress\nvisitors. He probably has read more\nbooks for each jear of his life than any\nbody In Congress because he got an\nearlier start. The first book he ever read\nwas Burton's Anatomy of Melancholy\nat an age. mind you, when his playmates\nwere Just beginning to take an interest\nin the Rollo, books. By tho time he was\ntwelve J'ears old Weaver could repeat\nnearly all of Shakespeare from memorj'-\nMaurice Splaln. after thirty jears of\nlong, hustling hours as an astute and\npainstaking Washington political corre\nspondent, found himself the I'nlted States\nMarshal for the District of Columbia.\nThe hours were uhort and the work light.\nFor jears Maurice had thought how nice\nit would be to hold a j b that paid a\ncomfortable salary without much to do\nNow he had Just such a place Along\ntoward 9 on the evening of his first\nday In office. Splaln met his friend, Hast\nings MacAdam. of the frt. I-ouis Repub\nlic. \"Come on.\" Splaln greeted him. effu\nslvelj \"let's go and have a little lum.li\nand a chat.\"\n\"Lunch\" Watchuh talkin' about,\nlunch\" \"aid MacAdam, \"it Isn t 10\no'clock jet. If I were like jou and\ndidn t have to work for a living. I would,\ngladly See me at midnight when I'm\nall through for the day and I 11 be\npleased to have lunch w Ith j ou\n\"You're right, v ou re right. muttered\nSplaln \"I dldn t realize It was so early\nIII meet jou when jou re through\nwork\n\"But.\" he added, gloomily. \"I don t sec\nhow I'm going to put In the time for the\nnext couple of hours\nRepresentative Samuel E. Wlnslow,\nskate-maker of Worcester. Mas\" is said\nto be the best after-dinner speaker in\nNew England The chances are that he\nIs also the best In Washington He is\none of the few after-dinner speakers we\never heanl. who. In manner and lan\nguage. Is really and truly funny\n(O